  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Recommendation for Zhao to Assume the Post of Commissioner of Hwazhou
  author: Choi Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A proclamation is hereby issued.

    In ancient times, Zhang Xu's son, Chong, in his youth loved to hunt. With a hawk perched upon his right arm and a hound led by his left hand, he ventured forth to the chase. His father, observing this, spoke to him saying: "With one body attending to two pursuits, is this not a burden to you?"

    Chong knelt and replied: "A man of worth establishes himself at thirty. I am now but twenty-nine. Grant me until the coming year, and I shall abandon these ways."

    Zhang Xu then said: "To err and yet possess the capacity to correct oneself—this is the way of the sage Yan. Through such transformation, one becomes worthy."

    Thereafter, Chong reformed his conduct and cultivated his character, eventually becoming a person of virtue and distinction. Thus the exemplary figures of antiquity remain worthy models for our own time.

    This official before us has likewise turned from the path of confusion and devoted himself to righteousness. Having cast aside his former doubts and hesitations, his contrition is most commendable. One who honors his parents as he serves his sovereign shall surely govern well when given office. Let him be appointed to assist in high counsel, that we may test his sincerity. Now, at a time when he may provide for his family and enjoy the fruits of virtue, let him prove himself through diligent service. Should he continue to excel and remedy his former failings, he shall bring peace to his family and kindle no discord in the realm.

    Therefore, it is ordained that Zhao shall assume the post of Commissioner of Hwazhou.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhang Xu (張緖) and his son Chong were historical figures known for representing the transformation from youthful excess to mature virtue, a common exemplum in classical Chinese moral philosophy.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Yan (顔氏子, the Yan clan) alludes to Yan Hui, Confucius's most virtuous disciple, embodying the ideal of self-correction and moral cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: This document appears to be an official commendation and appointment letter, a common genre in classical East Asian administrative writing, praising the recipient's moral reform and recommending his advancement.
